{
  "id": "019d33f2-ea7a-7eb1-8933-d4b13ef32a9c",
  "content": "# Buffered Access Tracking -- Design Decisions (Issue #12)\n\n## What: Replace direct Redb writes in LiteStore's record_access() with DashMap buffer + periodic flush.\n\n## Key Decisions:\n1. Buffer lives inside LiteStore (not at retriever level) -- keeps QueryableStore trait unchanged, PostgresStore unaffected.\n2. DashMap over Mutex<HashMap> -- sharded locking provides better throughput for write-heavy access pattern (~50-200ns vs lock contention).\n3. No background tokio task -- opportunistic flush on record_access() calls. Avoids requiring runtime handle in LiteStore.\n4. Dual flush triggers: time-based (60s) OR size-based (256 entries), whichever first.\n5. AtomicU64 CAS for single-writer flush exclusion -- only one concurrent flush runs.\n6. Lossy under pressure: if buffer full + flush in progress, drop the event silently (access tracking is optimization, not correctness).\n7. Graceful shutdown via LiteStore::Drop -- flush_sync() added alongside existing HNSW flush.\n\n## Alternatives Rejected:\n- Mutex<HashMap>: Higher contention under concurrent access.\n- mpsc channel: More complex lifecycle, requires tokio runtime handle, no easy pending count inspection.\n- Background interval task: Adds lifecycle complexity without benefit (opportunistic flush sufficient when search traffic exists).\n- Retriever-level buffer: Would require changing trait contract and duplicating logic for PostgresStore.",
